Oceania
-------
[6] New Zealand (Christchurch)
Date: Wed 18 Mar 2015
Source: The Press [edited]
http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/67439942/Second-measles-case-confirmed-in-Christchurch


A pre-school in Sumner, Christchurch has reported a case of measles. A 2-year-old girl enrolled at Pebbles Montessori and Pebbles Preschool had contracted the highly infectious disease (measles), centre director Belinda Slade said. The case was confirmed at 5 pm on [Wed 18 Mar 2015].

About 80 children were enrolled across both preschools. On the preschool's Facebook page parents were advised to keep children who had not been immunised away until 1 Apr 2015. Slade said the affected girl had received her 1st measles vaccine.

The Sumner case comes just 10 days after the Canterbury District Health Board confirmed a Christchurch child had been diagnosed with measles. That case was believed to be the 1st case of measles in the region since 2011.

Measles starts with fever, runny nose, cough, red eyes, and sore throat. It is followed by a rash that spreads over the body. Measles virus is highly contagious and spreads through the air through coughing and sneezing.

Canterbury medical officer of health Dr Daniel Williams urged parents to ensure children were immunised. "We need to keep lifting our rates of immunisation across the board if we are to be successful in eradicating measles."

[Byline: Cate Broughton]

